Project: Decision Trees and Random Forest - Predicting Potential Customers¶

Marks: 30¶

Welcome to the project on classification using decision trees and random forests.

Context¶

The EdTech industry has been surging in the past decade immensely, and according to a forecast, the Online Education market would be worth $286.62bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 10.26% from 2018 to 2023. The modern era of online education has enforced a lot in its growth and expansion beyond any limit. Due to having many dominant features like ease of information sharing, personalized learning experience, transparency of assessment, etc, it is now preferable to traditional education.

The online education sector has witnessed rapid growth and is attracting a lot of new customers. Due to this rapid growth, many new companies have emerged in this industry. With the availability and ease of use of digital marketing resources, companies can reach out to a wider audience with their offerings. The customers who show interest in these offerings are termed as leads. There are various sources of obtaining leads for Edtech companies, like

  • The customer interacts with the marketing front on social media or other online platforms.
  • The customer browses the website/app and downloads the brochure
  • The customer connects through emails for more information.

The company then nurtures these leads and tries to convert them to paid customers. For this, the representative from the organization connects with the lead on call or through email to share further details.

Objective¶

ExtraaLearn is an initial stage startup that offers programs on cutting-edge technologies to students and professionals to help them upskill/reskill. With a large number of leads being generated on a regular basis, one of the issues faced by ExtraaLearn is to identify which of the leads are more likely to convert so that they can allocate resources accordingly. You, as a data scientist at ExtraaLearn, have been provided the leads data to:

  • Analyze and build an ML model to help identify which leads are more likely to convert to paid customers,
  • Find the factors driving the lead conversion process
  • Create a profile of the leads which are likely to convert

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of leads and their interaction details with ExtraaLearn. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: ID of the lead
  • age: Age of the lead
  • current_occupation: Current occupation of the lead. Values include 'Professional','Unemployed',and 'Student'
  • first_interaction: How did the lead first interact with ExtraaLearn. Values include 'Website', 'Mobile App'
  • profile_completed: What percentage of the profile has been filled by the lead on the website/mobile app. Values include Low - (0-50%), Medium - (50-75%), High (75-100%)
  • website_visits: How many times has a lead visited the website
  • time_spent_on_website: Total time spent on the website
  • page_views_per_visit: Average number of pages on the website viewed during the visits.

  • last_activity: Last interaction between the lead and ExtraaLearn.

    • Email Activity: Seeking details about the program through email, Representative shared information with a lead like a brochure of program, etc.
    • Phone Activity: Had a Phone Conversation with a representative, Had a conversation over SMS with a representative, etc.
    • Website Activity: Interacted on live chat with a representative, Updated profile on the website, etc.

  • print_media_type1: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Newspaper.

  • print_media_type2: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Magazine.
  • digital_media: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn on the digital platforms.
  • educational_channels: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn in the education channels like online forums, discussion threads, educational websites, etc.
  • referral: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn through reference.
  • status: Flag indicating whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not.

Building Classification Models¶

Before training the model, let's choose the appropriate model evaluation criterion as per the problem at hand.

Model evaluation criterion¶

Model can make wrong predictions as:¶

  1. Predicting a lead will not converted to a paid customer in reality, the lead would have converted to a paid customer.
  2. Predicting a lead will converted to a paid customer in reality, the lead would not have converted to a paid customer.

Which case is more important?¶

  • If we predict that a lead will not get converted and the lead would have converted then the company will lose a potential customer.

  • If we predict that a lead will get converted and the lead doesn't get converted the company might lose resources by nurturing false positive cases.

Losing a potential customer is a greater loss for the organization.

How to reduce the losses?¶

  • Company would want Recall to be maximized, greater the Recall score higher are the chances of minimizing False Negatives.

Also, let's create a function to calculate and print the classification report and confusion matrix so that we don't have to rewrite the same code repeatedly for each model.

In [27]:
#function to print classification report and get confusion matrix in a proper format

def metrics_score(actual, predicted):
    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels=['Not Converted', 'Converted'], yticklabels=['Not Converted', 'Converted'])
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Let's check the performance on test data to see if the model is overfitting.

In [30]:
#Checking performance on the testing data
y_pred_test1 = d_tree.predict(X_test)
metrics_score(y_test, y_pred_test1)

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.87      0.86      0.87       962
           1       0.69      0.70      0.70       422

    accuracy                           0.81      1384
   macro avg       0.78      0.78      0.78      1384
weighted avg       0.81      0.81      0.81      1384

Observations:

  • The model is overfitting.
  • Precision and recall values for both vlass 0 and class 1 are a lot lower than in training data, indicating that the model is overfitting.
    • This model is not generalizing well enough. We need to adjust the max_depth of the tree.
  • Out of 422 converted leads, 126 were predicted as not converted. This is a low recall value of 0.70. We have a lot of false negatives, this really hurts the company as it could represent lost customers. We definitely want to adjust our decision tree so it does not overfit as much and reduce the false negative errors. A f1-score of 0.70 is not enough and could represent losses for the company.
  • Out of all the not converted customers, most were predicted correctly, with precision and recall of 0.87/0.86. This is very good, but can still be improved. However, these errors are a lot less dangerous than false negatives.
    • We probably need to weight class 0 and class 1.

Let's try hyperparameter tuning using GridSearchCV to find the optimal max_depth in order to reduce overfitting of the model. We can tune some other hyperparameters as well.

Decision Tree - Hyperparameter Tuning¶

We will use the class_weight hyperparameter with value equal to {0:0.3, 1:0.7} which is approximately the opposite of the imbalance in the original data.

This would tell the model that 1 is the important class here.

In [31]:
# Choose the type of classifier 
d_tree_tuned = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=7, class_weight={0:0.3, 1:0.7})

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {'max_depth': np.arange(2,10), 
              'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
              'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10, 20, 25]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations - recall score for class 1
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label=1)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(d_tree_tuned, parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the classifier to the best combination of parameters
d_tree_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data
d_tree_tuned.fit(X_train, y_train)
Out[31]:
DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight={0: 0.3, 1: 0.7}, criterion='entropy',
                       max_depth=3, min_samples_leaf=5, random_state=7)

We have tuned the model and fit the tuned model on the training data. Now, let's check the model performance on the training and testing data.

weighted avg       0.83      0.80      0.80      1384

Observations:

  • All the values are almost identical to the training data set results. This means that our model is generalizing properly and not overfitting.
    • The precision, recall and f1-score values for class 0 are: 0.93, 0.77 and 0.84 here versus 0.94, 0.77 and 0.85 in the training set.
    • The precision, recall and f1-score values for class 0 are: 0.62, 0.86 and 0.72 here versus 0.62, 0.88 and 0.73 in the training set.
  • The model minimizes false negatives: it has a high 0.86 class 1 recall score, which is what we want. Out out 422 converted leads, it predicted 365 properly. The amount of lost customers is a lot less than in the previous model (which had 126 converted leads misclassified). This means that this model is less costly than the previous one, as this error represents more cost to the company.
  • Out of 962 not converted leads, 224 got misclassified. While higher than the previous model's test results, this error is not nearly as costly as the previously mentioned one.
    • Because of this, we can conclude that this tuned tree is a lot better and less costly than the previous one.
    • Having max depth and minimum samples helped reduce overfitting, adding weight to class 1 helped prioritize it. All in all, this hyperparameter tuning was a positive.
    • The model could still be improved, but this is a significant improvement over the previous one.

Let's visualize the tuned decision tree and observe the decision rules:

Question 5: Write your observations from the below visualization of the tuned decision tree (3 Marks)¶

In [34]:
features = list(X.columns)

plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))

tree.plot_tree(d_tree_tuned,feature_names=features,filled=True,fontsize=9,node_ids=True,class_names=True)
plt.show()

Note: Blue leaves represent the converted customers i.e. y[1], while the orange leaves represent the not converted customers i.e. y[0]. Also, the more the number of observations in a leaf, the darker its color gets.

Observations:

  • In the top node there is an entropy of 1. This represents a high number of impurity with the data, at this point we cannot predict properly without a lot of entropy.
    • The top level attribute we are checking is first_interaction_Website. This means that this attribute has high Information Gain and will reduce the entropy the most. If a lead's first interaction was via website this will let us know the most about whether they are going to convert or not, it will give us the most information. When we did our variate analysis, we saw that this category had a significant difference on conversion rates vs user whose first interaction was via the mobile app.
    • Users whose first interaction was not with the website are more likely to be not converted customers than the other way around.
  • time_spent_on_website is the next variable that is checked, no matter the outcome of our first node. Both nodes check with a value between 415 and 420, so pretty similar. The entropy is reduced significantly on the orange node, there are a lot more class 0 leads than class 1. On the other node on the right side, the entropy is a lot higher (0.926). Predictions and results are more impure than on the left (0.737). The amount of class 1 leads vs class 0 is not as different as on the other node.
    • This feature seems to be very important for determining whether a lead will convert or not. The entropy is still very high, but its information gain at that stage was higher than other attributed which haven't yet been checked.
  • The next level has a lot of different nodes. On both extremes, age is checked. On the left branch, age has a very low entropy of 0.1, and the vast majority of leads are not converted customers, as can be seen by its dark orange color. This also has a homogenous leaf. Node #4 only has class y[0] (not converted leads) values. These leads checked via this age threshold, who spend less than 420 minutes on the website and did not make the first contact via website, are more than likely (in this case with an entropy of 0, so no impurity) to not convert and enroll. Node #3's entropy is higher than its parent and a lot higher than node #4. The age node on the right branch (node #12) has a significantly lower entropy than its parent. Professionals over the age of 25 tend to be y[1], converted leads (this was also seen on our previous analysis). The entropy of node #14 is not as low as node #4 but still an improvement. The dark blue color represents that most of the leads here are converted customers. Node #13 has a very high entropy and its color is white with a tinge of orange: leads who fall on this leaf can be either class (with a slight preference for y[0]). This is the reason why the entropy/impurity is so high on this node.
  • Profile completed medium leads node #9 has a lot of entropy (almost 1). Its color is almost white, you cannot really tell if leads there are not converted or converted. However, this decision rule can also help reduce entropy, as can be seen in nodes #10 and #11, where entropy is a lot lower and they have a clear blue or orange color. After checking first contact medium and time spent, profile completion is a good metric to reduce entropy and determine whether a lead will convert or not.
  • node #5 has a high entropy, and its color is white with a small tinge of orange. You cannot really tell if leads here are going to convert or not, even if there is a slight preference for not converting. This decision rule to see if their last activity was via website is also not as good as the other decision rules at its depth level. Both node #6 and node #7 have a high entropy level (and their colors aren't as strong as most of the other leafs), it can help classify more accurately but it is not the best decision rule at its depth level.
  • Decision trees are a lot easier to interpret and understand than other models. Via a statistycal analysis and understanding some of the data, these diagrams can be explained and understood; this can really help create business value and make this a good model.

Let's see if we can get a better model by tuning the random forest classifier:

Random Forest Classifier - Hyperparameter Tuning¶

Let's try tuning some of the important hyperparameters of the Random Forest Classifier.

We will not tune the criterion hyperparameter as we know from hyperparameter tuning for decision trees that entropy is a better splitting criterion for this data.

In [40]:
# Choose the type of classifier
rf_estimator_tuned = RandomForestClassifier(criterion="entropy", random_state=7)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {"n_estimators": [100, 110, 120],
    "max_depth": [5, 6, 7],
    "max_features": [0.8, 0.9, 1]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations - recall score for class 1
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label=1)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(rf_estimator_tuned, parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the classifier to the best combination of parameters
rf_estimator_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

Question 7:¶

  • Tune the random forest classifier using GridSearchCV (2 Marks)
  • Check the performance on both training and testing data (2 Marks)

In [43]:
# Choose the type of classifier
rf_estimator_tuned = RandomForestClassifier(criterion="entropy", random_state=7)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {"n_estimators": [110, 120],
    "max_depth": [6, 7],
    "min_samples_leaf": [20, 25],
    "max_features": [0.8, 0.9],
    "max_samples": [0.9, 1],
    "class_weight": [{0:0.7, 1:0.3}, "balanced", {0:0.4, 1:0.1}]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations - recall score for class 1
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label=1)

# Run the grid search on the training data using scoring=scorer and cv=5
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(rf_estimator_tuned, parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Save the best estimator to variable rf_estimator_tuned
rf_estimator_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

#Fit the best estimator to the training data
rf_estimator_tuned.fit(X_train, y_train)

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 8:¶

Write your conclusions on the key factors that drive the conversion of leads and write your recommendations to the business on how can they improve the conversion rate. (5 Marks)

Conclusions:

  • We did univariate and bivariate analysis with the data sets we had. From this, we could see that most leads were over 50, professionals or unemployed and were looking to expand their horizons.
    • Our bivariate analysis let us determine that users who start on the website and spend more time on it, of older age and with a high profile completion are the most likely to convert. Other values such as whether they had a referral seemed to be important as well, but they didn't have enough data to conclude.
  • Afterwards, we determined that the most costly errors where false negatives: classifying a converted customer as not converted. This would be bad as it means lost customers and money. The other error means wasting resources on not converting leads, which is also costly but not as much.
    • Because of this, we need to weigh the classes properly.
  • Our decision trees overfitted at first. After adjusting and having max_depth, our best decision tree determined that the 3 most relevant variables by far were: time spent on website, whether a user's first interaction was on the website, and if they completed their profile up to a medium level. Other variables such as age and whether their last interaction was on the website where relevant as well, but not as much. The rest of the variables were considered non-important by the model.
  • Our best random forest determined that the same variables were relevant, along with last phone activity, current occupation, website visits and page views per visit. Whether they had heard about the platform from education channels and they barely completed their profile were considered, but not as much as all the others.
  • Our best model in terms of reducing overall costs was the last random forest with hyperparameter tuning. The decision tree was good, easy to interpret and had a slightly (0.01) higher class 1 recall value. But the random forest had a much better class 0 recall, which could also be costly even if less so (wasting resources on not converting leads is still costly). Once considered all the costs and the random forest's protection against data changed, we believe that the last random forest is the best model.
  • In general, from all of the different analysis we did, we can conclude that the most important factors, in order, are:
    • The medium interaction. Do leads interact from the website, or phone? Where did they make their first contact? How much time do they spend in the website? In general, constant contact with the website and first approach being via it seem to be factors driving up conversion rate. Website seems to be attractive to leads who end up enrolling. This is a very important factor.
    • The profile completion is another important factor. Whether users take the time to complete their profile to a medium level seems to be relevant in determining whether they will convert or not.
    • Age and occupation were also a common factor. Most leads seem to be working age professionals, and whether they were employed, unemployed or students also plays a strong roll on their conversion rate.
    • These are the most important factors which were common denominators in all the analysis done: whether it was via univariate and bivariate analysis, decision tree importance or random forest.

Recommendations:

  • Based on the last point from the conclusions, we can make a lot of recommendations.
  • The website seems to be very important to converting leads, starting from the first approach. Leads who start with the mobile app do not seem to convert as much. Maybe the app's design and options are a lot less attractive to users, or maybe users only download the app once enrolled. The app could possibly be improved to match it, or a lot more ads budget could go to ads which redirect to the website instead of app download links. The strategy can be changed to either improve app, or prioritize website for a user's first contact with the platform.
  • Constant interactions with the website seem to be important, offers and ads that send leads to it could improve conversion rate.
  • There is not enough referral data to conclude much, but the few users who joined via referrals seemed to enroll more often than not. Incentivizing users to do more referrals via promotions or rewards could be a good way to get more conversions, and will also help the company get more data for better models.
  • Incentives to keep users for longer on the website can also bring up the conversion rate. Having attractive options for other courses so they check them out, special offers on display, etc. This can bring up their visit time, which seems to be an important factor.
  • Incentives to make users improve their profile can also be added. Users who have completed at least half of it seem to be more likely to enroll. Adding connectivity with other social media and other similar strategies could be used to improve this front.
  • Targetting professionals and unemployed leads of older age seems to be more effective than younger (under 30 years old) students.
